WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.880
Who am I and why am I talking to you about broom? I interned at RStudio over the last

00:00:13.880 --> 00:00:17.959
summer and worked on the broom package and have since taken over maintaining it. So if

00:00:17.959 --> 00:00:22.000
there's any bugs, send them to me and I will try and fix them. And also the person who

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:26.799
originally wrote broom is at RStudio conference. It's David Robinson. So give him a big shout

00:00:26.799 --> 00:00:30.840
out if you use broom at some point. Um, but I'm going to talk to you about what I'm calling

00:00:30.840 --> 00:00:37.520
the model representation problem and how broom kind of alleviates that to some degree. If

00:00:37.520 --> 00:00:40.720
you want to follow along with the slides, these are available online and you can download

00:00:40.720 --> 00:00:49.439
them. Okay. So anyway, what is the model representation problem? So if you have spent some time in

00:00:49.439 --> 00:00:54.000
a stat class or maybe even reading some tutorials online, uh, you will probably see things like

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:58.360
this somewhere. Here I've said, okay, there's this YI and I'm using this little tilde, which

00:00:58.360 --> 00:01:02.759
means that this Y is a random variable and it has a normal distribution. And so you can

00:01:02.759 --> 00:01:07.360
write this down. And if you've seen this before, you probably know what it means. And similarly,

00:01:07.360 --> 00:01:11.839
you can kind of like pick one normal distribution. We have standard notation for that. And

00:01:11.839 --> 00:01:16.599
when we have like a way to kind of represent factors of parameters and you can write down

00:01:16.599 --> 00:01:20.160
estimates. So in my mind, there's like these kind of three key objects. We have like

00:01:20.160 --> 00:01:23.599
models and then we have like individual fits for models and we have estimators, which I don't

00:01:23.599 --> 00:01:27.279
want to get into too much, but you can write these things down in ways that other people

00:01:27.279 --> 00:01:31.739
understand. So that's the, the kind of takeaway is that when you think of these things in

00:01:31.739 --> 00:01:36.080
terms of math, we have shared notation and community standards for how we write these

00:01:36.080 --> 00:01:44.519
things down. Yeah. So, uh, but in, in code, that's not the case quite as much as one would

00:01:44.519 --> 00:01:49.440
hope. Um, and so it's just a quick example. So one thing that you might imagine they might

00:01:49.440 --> 00:01:53.839
want to do is if you have like some classification model, you might want to get a class

00:01:53.839 --> 00:01:59.800
probabilities for that model. Okay. But, uh, that's kind of hard to do sometimes. So most of

00:01:59.800 --> 00:02:03.879
the time you can get class probabilities, but the question is how do you get class

00:02:03.879 --> 00:02:09.320
probabilities? So what I have here is, uh, some example that I have stolen from Max, but

00:02:09.320 --> 00:02:13.039
you have these different, uh, objects or models that you'd like to predict from. And if you

00:02:13.039 --> 00:02:17.479
want to get class probabilities, there's all of these different kind of interfaces, right? So

00:02:17.479 --> 00:02:21.119
it's not a question of whether or not you can do what you'd like to do. It's really a

00:02:21.119 --> 00:02:25.960
question of cognitive load. I don't want to have to remember all the different type

00:02:25.960 --> 00:02:29.600
arguments when I want to get class probabilities. Really. I just like to sit down and say,

00:02:29.600 --> 00:02:33.520
remember one thing and always get what I want. Okay. So what's happening is there's this

00:02:33.520 --> 00:02:38.080
extra friction that takes time away from being productive towards your end goal, which is

00:02:38.080 --> 00:02:44.039
really just like get the class probabilities and then get done with your job, right? Okay. So

00:02:44.039 --> 00:02:46.839
this is kind of what I'm calling the model representation problem is like we don't have a

00:02:46.839 --> 00:02:53.639
standard way to represent these things. Okay. And Broom is here to help. So Broom is, uh, a

00:02:53.639 --> 00:02:58.360
package written by David Robinson and there's these kind of three key ideas. The idea is

00:02:58.360 --> 00:03:03.600
that, uh, we can take these fits by fit. What I mean is, um, you have some model and you

00:03:03.600 --> 00:03:08.399
like train a model and you give me a trained model back. Okay. And we're going to say

00:03:08.399 --> 00:03:12.600
that there's kind of like three key components in this like Broom philosophy and we're

00:03:12.600 --> 00:03:16.199
going to, all of these components are going to be tidy tibbles. And the reason I'm going to be

00:03:16.199 --> 00:03:20.320
tidy tibbles is because we know how to manipulate tibbles and so we can use tools that we

00:03:20.320 --> 00:03:24.160
already know and there isn't any kind of additional cognitive load in working with those

00:03:24.160 --> 00:03:29.660
things. So the first type of information about a fit is going to be like the components or

00:03:29.660 --> 00:03:33.320
the parameters. So if you have a linear regression model, you could think about the

00:03:33.320 --> 00:03:36.360
regression coefficients. So we're going to have a table that's going to have all the

00:03:36.360 --> 00:03:42.440
information about the regression coefficients. Okay. And, uh, there's a S3 generic that

00:03:42.440 --> 00:03:46.419
will provide that to us. So that'll be tidy and I'll show some examples of how this works in

00:03:46.419 --> 00:03:53.660
just a moment. Okay. The second generic is glance. So glance is going to always return a

00:03:53.660 --> 00:03:59.399
tibble with one row and the columns are going to be different goodness of fit measures. So

00:03:59.399 --> 00:04:04.339
for example, this could be things like R squared or log likelihood or BIC or whatever kind

00:04:04.339 --> 00:04:10.199
of fancy version of, you know, information criteria that a model returns. Um, but it's a

00:04:10.240 --> 00:04:15.580
one row summary of the entire model. And then finally there's going to be this third

00:04:15.580 --> 00:04:20.079
generic that's augment. And what augment does is it says, well, you have this training

00:04:20.079 --> 00:04:24.959
data set and each one of the rows in this training data set influenced the final model in

00:04:24.959 --> 00:04:29.119
some way. So any of that information about how it influenced the final model is going to

00:04:29.119 --> 00:04:32.619
show up in augment. Or if you have new data, you can also use it to get predictions on new

00:04:32.619 --> 00:04:37.839
data in a kind of nice way. Okay. So we'll work through a kind of simple example here

00:04:37.839 --> 00:04:44.779
first. So, uh, suppose we have some data we can simulate from a normal distribution here

00:04:44.779 --> 00:04:51.260
and then we can get a fit where now this normal fit object here represents the maximum

00:04:51.260 --> 00:04:56.260
likelihood estimator of the parameters of this model. Okay. So the question is like, if we

00:04:56.260 --> 00:04:59.899
didn't do anything, like what did this thing look like? And if we look at this normal fit

00:04:59.899 --> 00:05:04.640
object, what we get is a list and I've cut off some of it, but we have these things in here.

00:05:04.640 --> 00:05:08.500
So there's this, um, we have our estimates, the maximum likelihood estimates themselves, and

00:05:08.500 --> 00:05:11.540
then we have their standard deviations and the covariance and the log likelihood of this

00:05:11.540 --> 00:05:15.920
model. Okay. So this is like actually a pretty nice object and you can work with it if you

00:05:15.920 --> 00:05:20.420
choose to, but the big issue is that if you go to a different package, it could look really

00:05:20.420 --> 00:05:25.059
different. Right? So as an example of something that's going to look really different,

00:05:25.059 --> 00:05:28.859
actually not as an example, that we'll get there in just a second. Um, we're going to talk

00:05:28.859 --> 00:05:33.859
about linear models first. Oh wow. Okay. I'm out of order, but here's what happens when we

00:05:33.880 --> 00:05:36.880
want to tidy this thing up. Right? So we'd like to have a table that represents these

00:05:36.880 --> 00:05:40.660
estimates. Right? So there's this normal fit and what we can do is if we call tidy on it,

00:05:40.660 --> 00:05:44.959
broom is going to clean it up for us. Okay. So here we get is this table and there's three

00:05:44.959 --> 00:05:48.859
columns and these column names are pretty much always going to be the same, which is going to

00:05:48.859 --> 00:05:52.559
be really nice. So we're going to have this term column and that's going to tell us what

00:05:52.559 --> 00:05:56.239
parameter we're actually working with. We're going to have the estimate that's going to tell

00:05:56.239 --> 00:05:59.940
us the actual value that we've calculated that we think we should be using. And we'll get a

00:05:59.959 --> 00:06:04.000
standard error, which is going to address our uncertainty, uncertainty in that parameter.

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:08.640
Okay. So I told you that there were two other generics that we can apply to these objects. So

00:06:08.640 --> 00:06:12.239
another one is glance. So for kind of a simple normal model, we only get some simple

00:06:12.239 --> 00:06:17.279
diagnostics. Here we see how many data we fit to the total log likelihood and then these

00:06:17.279 --> 00:06:21.140
other kind of criteria. Uh, there isn't actually an augment defined in broom at the moment

00:06:21.140 --> 00:06:23.880
for these univariate distributions, but you could think about these if you wanted to, like

00:06:23.880 --> 00:06:26.679
you could probably define like a log likelihood contribution if you wanted to think about

00:06:26.679 --> 00:06:31.720
that. Okay. So let's think about a slightly more involved model where this might start

00:06:31.720 --> 00:06:35.540
becoming more clear, like how it'll be useful in practice. So if you want to follow along on

00:06:35.540 --> 00:06:39.019
your computer, you can. This is, you only need these two lines. So we're going to create

00:06:39.019 --> 00:06:44.579
this, um, OLS fit object, which is going to be OLS estimators for the linear model. Okay. And

00:06:44.579 --> 00:06:48.579
uh, I can't actually print this out on a slide because this object is really big and

00:06:48.579 --> 00:06:54.019
complicated, but it's interesting to look into yourself if you kind of want to, or if you just

00:06:54.019 --> 00:06:57.320
want to be like intimidated by how crazy the internals are. So I still have no clue how it

00:06:57.320 --> 00:07:02.119
works. Okay. So, but then when you tidy it, you get something that's a lot easier to work

00:07:02.119 --> 00:07:07.059
with. You just get this table. Okay. So here we have the term again, the term is each one of

00:07:07.059 --> 00:07:10.279
our linear regression coefficients and we have this estimate, but now there's some

00:07:10.279 --> 00:07:14.779
additional information about linear models that we didn't have before. So we have these,

00:07:14.779 --> 00:07:20.160
um, uh, statistics from T tests and associated P values. If you wanted, you could also get

00:07:20.160 --> 00:07:24.200
confidence intervals. There is a argument to tidy that will give you those confidence

00:07:24.200 --> 00:07:29.660
intervals. Uh, when you glance at this, you also get a lot of information. So some of the

00:07:29.660 --> 00:07:32.160
metrics that you're going to get, you're going to get like R squared and adjusted R

00:07:32.160 --> 00:07:36.200
squared here. Sigma is the error variance, which is going to give you some measure of how

00:07:36.200 --> 00:07:40.739
uncertain predictions from this model are going to be and so on and so forth. And what

00:07:40.739 --> 00:07:45.359
exactly you get out is going to depend on the particular model that you put in. But the, uh,

00:07:45.359 --> 00:07:48.660
the column names are consistent. So if you want to like figure out how to get this

00:07:48.660 --> 00:07:52.359
information from one model or another, you don't have to remember what the internals of

00:07:52.359 --> 00:07:56.739
those two models look like. You can just tidy or glance them and then always just access

00:07:56.739 --> 00:08:03.279
that one column that you care about. Okay. Finally, I told you that there was this third

00:08:03.279 --> 00:08:08.119
generic augment. So if you call augment and you don't have any additional data, you can

00:08:08.119 --> 00:08:11.459
pass data into augment. But if you don't pass any data, it's going to root around in the

00:08:11.459 --> 00:08:15.820
model object and find the training data for your model. So in this case, what it's done is

00:08:15.820 --> 00:08:21.279
it's found that I used three columns from the original MT cars data set, HP, MPG and

00:08:21.279 --> 00:08:25.359
cylinder and it's going to put those into a data frame and then it's going to add

00:08:25.359 --> 00:08:29.519
additional information about each one of these observations. So here each row is an

00:08:29.519 --> 00:08:34.400
observation. You can see that there's a dot fitted column, which is going to be our

00:08:34.400 --> 00:08:38.359
actual prediction from the model. There's a dot SE fit, which is the standard error of

00:08:38.359 --> 00:08:42.479
that prediction and then so on and so forth. So for linear regression, there's a bunch of

00:08:42.700 --> 00:08:47.299
additional measures that we can add in here. But there's, these are all kind of like

00:08:47.299 --> 00:08:54.340
training data level summaries. Okay. So that's like the big picture of what Broom does

00:08:54.340 --> 00:08:58.719
and now I'd like to show you how I end up using Broom in practice. So the first thing that I

00:08:58.719 --> 00:09:03.320
do is I use it a lot when I want to do like a quick and dirty reporting tool. So if you are

00:09:03.320 --> 00:09:07.900
familiar with the knitter cable function, it's fantastic. It takes a data frame and then no

00:09:07.919 --> 00:09:12.859
matter kind of what you're outputting to, it just gives you like a nice table. And so if you

00:09:12.859 --> 00:09:17.159
can get your model into a table, which is exactly what tidy is going to do most of the

00:09:17.159 --> 00:09:21.700
time, you can report it really fast. So this is like my super quick and dirty. I don't want

00:09:21.700 --> 00:09:26.640
to just like barf our output into a homework document or something like that. So I'll use

00:09:26.640 --> 00:09:33.080
this kind of combination. The next thing that you can do is you can use Broom to compare

00:09:33.099 --> 00:09:40.239
different models by using this glance generic on a list of models all at once. So what I've

00:09:40.239 --> 00:09:44.239
done here is I've said, well let's put three different models in a list. I'm going to call

00:09:44.239 --> 00:09:49.919
them fit one, fit two and fit three. And in this case I'm adding more predictors at each step.

00:09:49.919 --> 00:09:56.380
Okay. And then I'm going to use this tool from the per package called map DF. And what that's

00:09:56.380 --> 00:10:01.880
going to do is it's going to apply the glance generic to each one of these models and then

00:10:01.919 --> 00:10:05.299
it's going to put them all into a data frame together. And I'm going to arrange it by the

00:10:05.299 --> 00:10:10.919
AIC. So if I look at the result, now I have a summary for each one of my models. And in

00:10:10.919 --> 00:10:15.500
this case it looks like AIC is the best model in term, that fit three is the best model in

00:10:15.500 --> 00:10:21.460
terms of AIC. I think that you can also plot this immediately for a really nice visual model

00:10:21.460 --> 00:10:26.460
comparison. Okay. By far my favorite use case for Broom is checking multiple linear

00:10:27.280 --> 00:10:34.659
regression. So I told you that if you use augment, you're going to get the residuals. And one

00:10:34.659 --> 00:10:37.239
of the things you might want to do when you're doing some sort of regression is you might

00:10:37.239 --> 00:10:40.780
want to take the residuals and compare them to each of your predictors and look at these

00:10:40.780 --> 00:10:44.280
partial residual plots. And if you're going to see any kind of systematic deviations there

00:10:44.280 --> 00:10:48.539
that might indicate some sort of model misfit. So if I want to do a visual check for model

00:10:48.539 --> 00:10:54.820
misfit, I have about ten lines of code here and it's going to produce the following plot. So

00:10:54.820 --> 00:10:59.179
that's it. And now I can look at these residuals and see if there's any patterns here. So if I

00:10:59.179 --> 00:11:03.719
kind of eyeball this, I wouldn't be too concerned in this case. But it's a nice way to do

00:11:03.719 --> 00:11:09.719
quick and easy diagnostics. Okay. So finally I'm going to work through kind of a more

00:11:12.219 --> 00:11:16.979
extended example. I don't actually have the time so if someone could let me know how much I

00:11:16.979 --> 00:11:20.679
have left, that would be great. But I'm going to work through this kind of more extended

00:11:20.679 --> 00:11:23.359
example which is where I think the real power of Broom comes in which is when you want to

00:11:23.400 --> 00:11:28.320
work with multiple models at once. Okay. So suppose we have this data. This is the MT

00:11:28.320 --> 00:11:31.820
cars data again. I'm sorry if you've seen this a hundred times. But if we want to think

00:11:31.820 --> 00:11:37.400
about the miles per gallon and weight, we could say well let's use a model here but we don't

00:11:37.400 --> 00:11:40.099
want to do a linear model. We could say this really looks like there's some sort of

00:11:40.099 --> 00:11:44.940
inverse relationship. Let's do some sort of like nonlinearly squares. So we could say well

00:11:44.940 --> 00:11:48.940
let's just use this model. So let's say there's like some inverse relationship with weight.

00:11:48.940 --> 00:11:52.679
The particular model here is not particularly important. But we could say well let's use

00:11:52.679 --> 00:11:57.460
this model and maybe we'd like to fit this a bajillion times on bootstrap data sets to see

00:11:57.460 --> 00:12:04.679
what the uncertainty in these parameters K and B is. Okay. So to do this the first thing

00:12:04.679 --> 00:12:09.460
that we're going to use is we're going to use the R sample package. And we're going to

00:12:09.460 --> 00:12:13.679
create bootstrap data sets. In this case we're going to create a hundred bootstrap data

00:12:13.679 --> 00:12:17.179
sets. And what we're going to get is we're going to get this tibble that has a bunch of

00:12:17.179 --> 00:12:22.760
nested objects. So when you start looking at kind of these R sample stuff there, you

00:12:22.760 --> 00:12:27.140
might wonder what's going on. So we have this split object. And so this split is going to

00:12:27.140 --> 00:12:31.219
have two kind of data sets contained in it. It's going to have the bootstrap data set and

00:12:31.219 --> 00:12:35.760
the held out data set. And then there's going to be this ID column. And so the idea is

00:12:35.760 --> 00:12:41.140
that we're going to use mutate together with per map to add new list columns of models and

00:12:41.140 --> 00:12:48.520
work with those new list columns of models. And a general strategy that works really well

00:12:48.520 --> 00:12:53.559
in these kind of circumstances is you figure out how to do something on one resampled data

00:12:53.559 --> 00:12:58.099
set. So what I've done here is there's a function in R that will let me fit a nonlinear least

00:12:58.099 --> 00:13:03.020
squares and it's called NLS. And so NLS is going to need three arguments. I have to kind

00:13:03.020 --> 00:13:07.440
of define the formula that I want to use. So in this case that's exactly the formula from

00:13:07.440 --> 00:13:12.479
the slides a couple before. And I have to tell it the data I want to use. So in this case

00:13:12.479 --> 00:13:17.440
there's that split object from my bootstraps data frame. And I'd like to use the analysis

00:13:17.440 --> 00:13:21.359
function to get the training set out of there. And finally because it's a kind of different

00:13:21.359 --> 00:13:24.239
model than usual, I have to give it some sort of initial parameters which don't really matter

00:13:24.239 --> 00:13:29.020
here. So this is the helper function that's going to solve this problem for me on one data

00:13:29.020 --> 00:13:34.140
set. So now I'd like to generalize this which I can just do with map. So now I take my

00:13:34.140 --> 00:13:39.719
bootstrap data sets and I'm going to mutate map. So now I'm going to fit a bootstrap data

00:13:39.719 --> 00:13:43.559
set on each one of these resampled data sets. And I'm going to do the second thing where

00:13:43.559 --> 00:13:47.840
now I have each one of these fit models and I'm going to tidy each one of these fit models

00:13:47.840 --> 00:13:53.880
here. So now what I've done is in this first row I have a data set. I have an ID that kind

00:13:53.880 --> 00:13:58.979
of corresponds to which data set it is. And then I have an S3 object. That's my actual model

00:13:58.979 --> 00:14:03.979
object which is living in this column. And then I'm going to have a nested table which has

00:14:03.979 --> 00:14:08.640
my tidied coefficients. So at first glance this kind of structure can seem really

00:14:08.640 --> 00:14:14.559
intimidating because you have all of these nested hierarchical structures. But this is kind

00:14:14.559 --> 00:14:18.359
of where you want to think about. You want to end up here and then there's a magical function

