answer questions or help with pull requests or anything at any time. So I've got my contact

00:16:22.039 --> 00:16:23.539
information up here as well. Thank you.

00:16:23.539 --> 00:16:37.919
Cool. If you go to my Twitter, I should have just tweeted out. Okay.

00:16:38.260 --> 00:16:42.140
So thanks, Alex. We have time for a couple questions.

00:16:51.380 --> 00:16:54.539
Maybe stand up and wave at me if you do have one. Yeah, okay, back here.

00:16:54.539 --> 00:17:14.959
Can you hear me? Can you hear me, anybody? Okay, here we are. So since you're bootstrapping

00:17:14.959 --> 00:17:18.199
with a Tibble, is that making it extremely efficient time wise?

00:17:18.199 --> 00:17:22.839
Okay, so there's two things you have to think about in terms of the efficiency for these

00:17:22.839 --> 00:17:26.880
things. The first is like the data. Are you going to create a bunch of copies of the data?

00:17:26.880 --> 00:17:30.500
And the answer is no. Max has implemented this in a way so you're not going to create

00:17:30.500 --> 00:17:33.839
excessive copies of the data. You're going to have to create a little bit of ‑‑ so I think

00:17:33.839 --> 00:17:37.500
the example is like if you bootstrap and you have 50 bootstrap data sets, you're going to have

00:17:37.500 --> 00:17:41.420
like maybe three times as much storage space as originally. What you're really going to get

00:17:41.420 --> 00:17:46.300
hit with in terms of inefficiency is going to be the models themselves. So most modeling

00:17:46.300 --> 00:17:51.699
functions in R, they actually save the data that they were fit on and that gets big really

00:17:51.699 --> 00:17:56.859
fast. So it really depends on how kind of clean the modeling package is. But that's

00:17:56.859 --> 00:18:00.400
normally not at your mercy. So if you're running into kind of space issues, one kind of

00:18:00.400 --> 00:18:03.859
standard thing you can do is you can define a helper function to fit the model, figure out

00:18:03.859 --> 00:18:07.280
what you actually need from that and then try to throw away as much junk as possible and

00:18:07.280 --> 00:18:13.280
kind of keep that like pared down object. I think we have time for one more question.

00:18:22.699 --> 00:18:28.699
Hi. Great talk. Can you just in a few sentences say what it takes to implement new tidiers?

00:18:32.619 --> 00:18:38.739
Yeah, normally it's about like five lines of tidyverse code in terms of like effort. So like

00:18:38.739 --> 00:18:42.079
five lines of tidyverse code and effort. The biggest thing is making sure that you're

00:18:42.079 --> 00:18:46.160
meeting the kind of conventions. So if you break with the convention, it doesn't actually do

00:18:46.160 --> 00:18:49.739
any good for anybody. So there's a lot of documentation. I need to update that to some

00:18:49.739 --> 00:18:56.239
extent. But this link that I have in the slides here should work you through everything you

00:18:56.239 --> 00:19:00.319
need to do. So I would say maybe 15 minutes to read through that and hopefully 30 minutes or

00:19:00.319 --> 00:19:06.319
less to create a custom one of your own. I think we can do one more quick question.

00:19:20.400 --> 00:19:27.400
I have a love-hate relationship with the boot package. But one thing that I like about it is

00:19:27.400 --> 00:19:33.900
that it's got support for computing different types of confidence intervals that have better

00:19:33.900 --> 00:19:40.280
properties that you would like in them. So I was wondering if these tools have anything like

00:19:40.280 --> 00:19:46.280
that implemented or if it's just kind of percentile confidence intervals and that sort of thing.

00:19:47.280 --> 00:19:52.739
So I didn't actually show a confidence interval example. What I visualized up on the board was

00:19:52.739 --> 00:19:58.900
the entire sampling distribution. So if you can, that's what my recommendation is, is to look

00:19:58.900 --> 00:20:02.780
at the whole sampling distribution. But when you're working with our sample, it's kind of low

00:20:02.780 --> 00:20:07.520
level infrastructure. So if you're going to do calculations across all of those coefficients

00:20:07.520 --> 00:20:13.520
at once, you'll need to implement that method yourself. Max has a comment as well.

00:20:16.280 --> 00:20:21.640
Oh, yeah, there's fancy stuff. There's like 632 coming. So there's fancy stuff coming. That will be really cool.

